1. Sensitivity, Specificity

Assume that there is 2 variables \(X,Y\) s.t \[\begin{eqnarray*} X & =& \left \{ \begin{array}{ccl} 1 & & \mbox{disease}\\ 2 & & \mbox{otherwise} \end{array} \right. \\ \\ Y & = &\left \{ \begin{array}{ccl} 1 & & \mbox{Test is Positive}\\ 2 & & \mbox{Test is Negative} \end{array} \right. \end{eqnarray*}\]

  • Sensitivity : \(P(Y=1 | X=1)\)
  • Specificity : \(P(Y=2 | X=2)\)

\(\Rightarrow\) The higher Sensitivity and Specificity implies the more accurate test is.

Disease = c("Disease","Normal")
Test = c("Positive","Negative")
ex_1 = expand.grid(Test=Test,Disease=Disease)
val_1 = c(9,1,89,1024)
table_1 = cbind(ex_1,count=val_1)
ex_tab_1= xtabs(formula = count ~ Test + Disease, data = table_1)
ex_tab_1
##           Disease
## Test       Disease Normal
##   Positive       9     89
##   Negative       1   1024
cat("The Sensitive is =", ex_tab_1[1,1]/(ex_tab_1[1,1]+ex_tab_1[2,1]), "and the Specificity is =", ex_tab_1[2,2]/(ex_tab_1[2,2]+ex_tab_1[1,2]))
## The Sensitive is = 0.9 and the Specificity is = 0.9200359

2. Observational study

  • Observation study : A method of observing who belongs to a group and what reaction results.
  • Ex1. Case control study : A study designed to look back on the past. (retrospective)
  • EX2. Clinical trial : Randomly assigns subjects to groups.
  • Ex3. Cohort study : (Prospective) After making each individual choose which group he or she belongs to, he or she are observed whether or not have outcome such as disease. The total number of each row \(N_{i+}\) is fixed.
  • Ex4. Cross-sectional study : (Prospective) Samples are collected and grouped according to group status and response variables at the same time. Total number N is fixed.
  • cf.Experimental study : After the researcher decides which subjects belong to each group, and analyzes the results.

3. Difference of Proportions(DP), Relative Risk(RR), Odds Ratio(O)

  • When \(DP\) is nearly zero on both groups, we need to consider \(RR\) or \(OR\)
  • Also even though \(DP\) are same, \(RR\) can be different.
  • EX. \(\pi_{1|1}=0.0100\), \(\pi_{1|2}=0.001\) vs. \(\pi_{1|1}=0.410\), \(\pi_{1|2}=0.401\) \(\rightarrow\) \(RR=10\) vs. \(RR=1.02\)
  • When the ratios of success are nearly zero on both groups, then \(OR\) is nearly same with \(RR\). \[OR = RR \times \frac{1p_2}{1p_1}\]
  • The relation between \(RR\) and OR is useful, for example, for certain design we cannot calculate RR instead we can estimate \(OR\) and using \(OR\) we can obtiain \(RR\) approximately.(under some condition, \(OR \approx RR\))
  • OR uses variables symmetrically so that we dont need to consider response and explanatory variables separately

Example. The association of aspirin with myocardial infarction

In one study, one group participants were asked to take aspirin while the other group were given placebo and researcher check whether myocardial infarction occurred during the study.

Disease = c("Disease","Normal")
Drug = c("Placebo","Aspirin")
ex_2 = expand.grid(Drug=Drug,Disease=Disease)
val_2 = c(189,104,10845,10933)
table_2 = cbind(ex_2,count=val_2)
ex_tab_2= xtabs(formula = count ~ Drug + Disease, data = table_2)
ex_tab_2
##          Disease
## Drug      Disease Normal
##   Placebo     189  10845
##   Aspirin     104  10933
ex_2_pi.1=  ex_tab_2[1,1]/(ex_tab_2[1,1]+ex_tab_2[1,2])
ex_2_pi.2=  ex_tab_2[2,1]/(ex_tab_2[2,1]+ex_tab_2[2,2])
cat("The DP is =",ex_2_pi.1- ex_2_pi.2, "and the RR is =", ex_2_pi.1/ex_2_pi.2, "and the OR is =", ex_2_pi.1/(1-ex_2_pi.1)/(ex_2_pi.2/(1-ex_2_pi.2) ))
## The DP is = 0.007706024 and the RR is = 1.817802 and the OR is = 1.832054
  • \(DP=0.007706024 > 0\) means : Taking aspirin reduces risk of Disease. (Note that, actually we need to consider confidence interval)
  • \(RR=1.817802\) means : The group who took placebo than the group taking aspirin is 82% more likely to develop the disease. (Easy to interpret.)
  • \(OR=1.832054\) means : The OR estimate for the placebo group = 1.83*the OR estimate for group taking aspirin. (little bit tricky but useful. For the general public, it is better to report relative risk because it is easier to interpret. )

Example. A research study estimated that under a certain condition, the probability that a subject would be referred for heart catheterization was 0.906 for whites and 0.847 for blacks.

  1. Find the odds ratio (odds AA get hc to odds whites get hc).
Catheterization = c("Yes","No")

ex_tab_2.11
##     Catheterization
## Race   Yes    No
##   AA 0.847 0.153
##   W  0.906 0.094
ex_2.11_pi.1=  ex_tab_2.11[1,1]/(ex_tab_2.11[1,1]+ex_tab_2.11[1,2])
ex_2.11_pi.2=  ex_tab_2.11[2,1]/(ex_tab_2.11[2,1]+ex_tab_2.11[2,2])
cat("The DP is =",ex_2.11_pi.1- ex_2.11_pi.2, "and the RR is =", ex_2.11_pi.1/ex_2.11_pi.2, "and the OR is =", ex_2.11_pi.1/(1-ex_2.11_pi.1)/(ex_2.11_pi.2/(1-ex_2.11_pi.2) ))
## The DP is = -0.059 and the RR is = 0.9348786 and the OR is = 0.5743699
  1. An associated Press story described the study and said Doctors were only 57% as likely to order cardiac catheterization for blacks as for whites. Is this the correct interpretation? If not, give the correct percentage for this interpretation.

  • \(Y_i \sim B(n_i, \pi_i)\)

  • \(\mbox{logit}(\pi_i(x_i)) = \log \frac{\pi_i(x_i)}{1-\pi_i(x_i)} = \alpha + \beta x_i\)

  • \(\pi_i(x) = \frac{\exp(\alpha + \beta x_i)}{1+\exp(\alpha + \beta_i x_i)}\)

  • run glm (family option in glm depends on distribution of response variable.)

snore.glm_logit = glm(cbind(yes,no) ~ snore,data=snore,family=binomial(link = "logit"))
#cf. glm(yes/(yes+no) ~ snore,data=snore,family=binomial(),weights=yes+no)

5. Inference for GLM: Deviance and Goodness of Fit

For logistic glm, we assume that \[\log \left( \frac{\pi(x)}{1-\pi(x)} \right) = \alpha + \beta x\] \(\Rightarrow\) we use 2 parameters.

  • Saturated model
    • Model with a perfect fit \(\hat{\mu}_i = y_i\), \(i=1, \ldots, n\)
    • Model with a maximum number of parameters
    • Used as a criterion to be compared to several other models
    • Contains more parameters than the our assumed model

  • LS : The maximum log likelihood value of the saturated model. Denote: \(\ell (y;y)\)

  • LM : The maximum log likelihood value of the assumed model. Denote: \(\ell(\hat{\mu} ;y)\)

\[ \mbox{LS} \mbox{LM} \]

  • Deviance : goodness-of-fit statistic for a statistical model. \[\mbox{Deviance}=D(y,\hat{\mu} ):=2(\mbox{LM}\mbox{LS})=2\log\frac{\ell (y;y)}{\ell(\hat{\mu};y)}\] That is, LRT for comparing a saturated model \(S\) and fitted model \(\hat{\mu}\)
    \(\Rightarrow\) It follws approximately \(\chi_{df}^2\) distribution, where \(df\)=difference number of the parameters (# of parameters in \(S\) - # of parameters in \(\hat{\mu}\)).

  • Statistic has high value, \(p\) has low value implies assumed model do not fit well.

snore.glm_logit
## 
## Call:  glm(formula = cbind(yes, no) ~ snore, family = binomial(link = "logit"), 
##     data = snore)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)        snore  
##     -3.8662       0.3973  
## 
## Degrees of Freedom: 3 Total (i.e. Null);  2 Residual
## Null Deviance:       65.9 
## Residual Deviance: 2.809     AIC: 27.06
  • Null Deviance means deviance difference between Saturated model and simple model( do not care of snoring effect)
Dev_logit<-snore.glm_logit$deviance
Dev_logit
## [1] 2.808912
1-pchisq(Dev_logit,2) 
## [1] 0.2455006

p>>0.05 means logistic model fits well.

  • want deviance residuals from the logit model?

    • Perason residual \[ r_{P_i} = \frac{y_i-\hat{\mu}_i}{sd(\hat{\mu}_i)}\]
    • When the model holds, Pearson and deviance residuals are less variable than standard normal

6. Introduction to Deep Learning (Using Keras)

cf.Neural Networks

  • Consider the neural network \(K\)-class classification model that has one hidden layer:

\[\begin{eqnarray*} z_m^{(0)} &=& b_m^{(0)} + \mathrm{w}_m^{(0)T} \mathrm{x}, &~ m=1, \ldots, M\\ h_m &=& \sigma(z_m^{(0)}), &~ m=1, \ldots, M\\ z_k^{(1)} &=& b_k^{(1)}+\mathrm{w}_k^{(1)T}\mathrm{h}, &~ k=1, \ldots, K\\ f_k(\mathrm{x}) &=& g_k(\mathrm{z}), &~ k=1, \ldots, K \end{eqnarray*}\] where \(\mathrm{x}=(x_1, \ldots, x_p)\), \(\mathrm{h}=(h_1, \ldots, h_M)\) and \(M\) is the number of class of hidden layer.

  • Notations
    • \(x_p\), \(i=1, \ldots, p\) : input node
    • \(h_m\), \(m=1,\ldots, M\) : hidden node
    • \(y_k\), \(k=1, \ldots, K\) : ouput (response) node
    • \(\mathrm{w}_m^{(0)}, \mathrm{w}_m^{(1)}\) : weight vector
    • \(b_m^{(0)}, b_m^{(1)}\) : bias
    • \(g_k\) : output function
  • \(\sigma(\cdot)\) is a nonlinear transformation which is the activation function.
    • Sigmoid function : \[ sigmoid(x) = \frac{\exp(x)}{1+\exp(x)} \]
    • tanh function : \[ tanh(x) = \frac{\exp(x) - \exp(-x)}{\exp(x) + \exp(-x)} \]
    • softmax function (classification case) : \[ g_k(\mathrm{z}) = \frac{\exp(z_k)}{\sum_{l=1}^{K}\exp(z_l)}, ~~ k=1,\ldots, K\]
    • Identity function (Regression case) : \[g_k(\mathrm{z})=\mathrm{z}, ~~ k=1, \ldots, K\]

1. Deep Neural Network Architecture

2. Data Augmentation

In Keras, We have a ImageDataGenerator class that is used to generate batches of tensor image data with real-time data augmentation. The data will be looped over (in batches) indefinitely. The image data is generated by transforming the actual training images by rotation, crop, shifts, shear, zoom, flip, reflection, normalization etc.

3. Regularization

Deep neural nets with a large number of parameters are very powerful machine learning systems. However, overfitting is a serious problem in such networks. Given below are few techniques which were proposed recently and has become a general norm these days in convolutional neural networks.

  • Dropout The key idea is to randomly drop units (along with their connections) from the neural network during training. The reduction in number of parameters in each step of training has effect of regularization.

  • Kernel_regularizer allows to apply penalties on layer parameters during optimization. These penalties are incorporated in the loss function that the network optimizes.

  • BatchNormalization normalizes the activation of the previous layer at each batch, i.e.applies a transformation that maintains the mean activation close to 0 and the activation standard deviation close to 1. It addresses the problem of internal covariate shift.

  • Polling

4. Notations

  • Epoch: One Epoch is when an ENTIRE dataset is passed forward and backward through the neural network only ONCE

  • Batch size: Total number of training examples present in a single batch.

  • Iteration: The number of passes to complete one epoch.

Hence, 1 epoch = (# of data/batch size) iterations.

library(keras)

# Parameters --------------------------------------------------------------

batch_size <- 64
epochs <- 10
data_augmentation <- TRUE
num_classes <- 10


# Data Preparation --------------------------------------------------------

# See ?dataset_cifar10 for more info
cifar10 <- dataset_cifar10()

# Feature scale RGB values in test and train inputs  
x_train <- cifar10$train$x/255
x_test <- cifar10$test$x/255

y_train <- to_categorical(cifar10$train$y, num_classes = 10)
y_test <- to_categorical(cifar10$test$y, num_classes = 10)


# Defining Model ----------------------------------------------------------

lr_schedule = function(epoch, lr){
  lrate = 0.001
  if(epoch > 50) {
    lrate = 0.0005
  }
  if(epoch > 100) {
    lrate = 0.0001
  } 
  if(epoch > 150){
    lrate = 0.00001
  }
  return(lrate)
}

# Initialize sequential model
model <- keras_model_sequential()

weight_decay = 1e-4

model %>%
  
  # Start with hidden 2D convolutional layer being fed 32x32 pixel images
  layer_conv_2d(
    filter = 32, kernel_size = c(3,3), padding = "same", kernel_regularizer = regularizer_l2(weight_decay), 
    input_shape = c(32, 32, 3)
  ) %>%
  layer_activation("elu") %>%
  
  # Second hidden layer
  layer_conv_2d(filter = 32, kernel_size = c(3,3), padding = "same", kernel_regularizer = regularizer_l2(weight_decay)) %>%
  layer_activation("elu") %>%
  
  # Use max pooling
  layer_max_pooling_2d(pool_size = c(2,2)) %>%
  layer_dropout(0.1) %>%
  
  # 2 additional hidden 2D convolutional layers
  layer_conv_2d(filter = 64, kernel_size = c(3,3),padding = "same", kernel_regularizer = regularizer_l2(weight_decay)) %>%
  layer_activation("elu") %>%
  layer_conv_2d(filter = 64, kernel_size = c(3,3), padding = "same", kernel_regularizer = regularizer_l2(weight_decay)) %>%
  layer_activation("elu") %>%
  
  # Use max pooling once more
  layer_max_pooling_2d(pool_size = c(2,2)) %>%
  layer_dropout(0.1) %>%
  
  # 3 additional hidden 2D convolutional layers
  layer_conv_2d(filter = 128, kernel_size = c(3,3),padding = "same", kernel_regularizer = regularizer_l2(weight_decay)) %>%
  layer_activation("elu") %>%
  layer_conv_2d(filter = 128, kernel_size = c(3,3), padding = "same", kernel_regularizer = regularizer_l2(weight_decay)) %>%
  layer_activation("elu") %>%
  
  # Use max pooling once more
  layer_max_pooling_2d(pool_size = c(2,2)) %>%
  layer_dropout(0.1) %>%
  
  
  # Flatten max filtered output into feature vector 
  # and feed into dense layer
  layer_flatten() %>%
  layer_dense(512) %>%
  layer_activation("elu") %>%
  
  # Outputs from dense layer are projected onto 10 unit output layer
  layer_dense(10) %>%
  layer_activation("softmax")

opt <- optimizer_rmsprop(lr = 0.0001, decay = 1e-6)

model %>% compile(
  loss = "categorical_crossentropy",
  optimizer = opt,
  metrics = "accuracy"
)


# Training ----------------------------------------------------------------

if(!data_augmentation){
  
  model %>% fit(
    x_train, y_train,
    batch_size = batch_size,
    epochs = epochs,
    validation_data = list(x_test, y_test),
    shuffle = TRUE,
    callbacks = callback_learning_rate_scheduler(lr_schedule)
  )
  
} else {
  
  datagen <- image_data_generator(
    rotation_range = 15,
    width_shift_range = 0.1,
    height_shift_range = 0.1,

  )
  
  datagen %>% fit_image_data_generator(x_train)

    flow_images_from_data(x_train, y_train, datagen, batch_size = batch_size),

    epochs = epochs, 
    validation_data = tuple(x_test, y_test),
    verbose=1,
    callbacks = callback_learning_rate_scheduler(lr_schedule),
    workers=1
  )
  
}
scores = evaluate(model, x_test, y_test)
print(paste('Test loss:', scores[1]))
print(paste('Test accuracy:', scores[2]))

7. Recurrent Neural Network (RNN)

  • RNN are a family of neural networks for processing sequential data
  • Predicted probability: \(p_t = softmax(c+Vh_t)\)
  • Hidden unit: \(h_t = tanh(b+ wh_{t-1}+Ux_t)\)
  • Hidden unit at time \(t\) (\(h_t\)) is a function of hidden unit at \(t-1\) and the input at time \(t\)
  • Unknown parameters (\(c,V,b,w,U\)) do not depend on time
  • Output unit: \(o_t = c+Vh_t\)
  • Backpropagation
  • Aplication of RNN
    • one to one : typical
    • one to many : image captioning (image to sequence of words)
    • many to one : sentiment analysis (sequence of words to sentiment)
    • many to many : with lag, machine translation (sequence of words to sequence of words)
  • Long Short-term Memory (LSTM)
    • LSTM allows long-term dependence in time
    • LSTM is designed to avoid the problem due to nonlinear relationship and the problem of gradient explosion
    • Notations
      • input gate: $i_t = (b + Ux_t + wh_{t-1})
      • forget gate: \(f_t=\sigma(b^f+U^fx_t+w^fh_{t-1})\)
      • new memory cell: $t=tanh(bg+Ugx_t+w^gh{t-1}) $
      • updated momory: \(c_t=f_tc_{t-1} + i_t\tilde{c}_t\)
      • ouput gate: \(o_t=\sigma(b^o+U^ox_t+w^oh_{t-1})\)
      • \(h_t = tanh(c_t)o_t\)
      • $p_t=softmax(c+Vh_t) $
